"en">Factiva Filters</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001000-20180323-161933"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:mcat"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001000-20180323-161933"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="nfce"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">C&amp;E Exclusion Filter</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001000-20180323-161933"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:mcat"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001000-20180323-161933"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">G/FED G/IGV G/TRE I/BNK I/IAV I/ZFU JPM M/FCL N/GEN N/GENI N/IEN N/PLT R/NME R/US </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday BAILOUT BEAR STEARNS CAPITAL REQUIREMENTS FED FEDERAL RESERVE FINANCIAL CRISIS INTEREST RATES MINNEAPOLIS FED NEEL KASHKARI RESCUES TARP TAXPAYERS TOO BIG TO FAIL TREASURY DEPARTMENT TROUBLED ASSET RELIEF PROGRAM SB1102709309303734354240458410599333184589813 Bass, Kyle Brown, Jerry Kashkari, Neel SYND CODES_REVIEWED Markets Main </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">OMKM OPOL </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Markets</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Fed Official Who Bailed Out Big Banks Is Now One of Their Biggest Critics; Neel Kashkari is proposing measures that could break up big banks</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>A <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ten-years-after-the-bear-stearns-bailout-nobody-thinks-it-would-happen-again-1520959233">decade after the financial crisis</ELink>, The Wall Street Journal has checked in on dozens of the bankers, government officials, chief executives, hedge-fund managers and others who left a mark on that period to find out what they are doing now. Today, we spotlight former Treasury Department administrator Neel Kashkari and hedge-fund manager Kyle Bass.</Para><Para>Neel Kashkari oversaw the bailout of big banks during <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ten-years-after-the-bear-stearns-bailout-nobody-thinks-it-would-happen-again-1520959233?mod=searchresults&amp;page=1&amp;pos=12">the financial crisis</ELink>. Now, as a Federal Reserve regional bank president, he is proposing measures that could break them up.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>In March 2008, he was a representative for the U.S. Treasury Department in negotiations to bring in JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co. to take over Bear Stearns after the financial firm's <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB120580966534444395">sudden collapse</ELink>. Later that year, Mr. Kashkari, who was 35 years old at the time, was in charge of <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/financial-crisis-lessons-of-the-rescuea-drama-in-five-acts-1378685098">the $700 billion Troubled Asset Relief Program</ELink>, launched during President George W. Bush's administration to buy up distressed assets in an effort to stave off banks from further financial ruin.</Para><Para>"The bailouts, while the right thing to do at the time, violated a core American belief: If you take a risk, you bear the consequences," Mr. Kashkari said in an interview last month. "A lot of political division we experience is still a byproduct of the financial crisis and the fundamental unfairness."</Para><Para>He said the experience changed some of his views and altered <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/neel-kashkari-to-be-named-new-minneapolis-fed-president-1447170684">the trajectory of his career</ELink>. Mr. Kashkari is now president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis.</Para><Para>"I went into the Bush administration considering myself a free-market person," Mr. Kashkari said. Now, "free markets are still preferred, but markets can make mistakes, sometimes large, costly ones. We do need some regulation to protect against free-market excesses such as those that lead to financial crises."</Para><Para>Mr. Kashkari has argued that rules designed to prevent taxpayer rescues of the financial system <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/minneapolis-feds-kashkari-says-must-consider-options-for-ending-too-big-to-fail-1459783192">haven't gone far enough</ELink>, and that "too-big-to-fail" banks remain ticking time bombs that could destabilize the economy.</Para><Para>He has recommended <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/feds-neel-kashkari-rolls-out-blueprint-for-ending-too-big-to-fail-banks-1479300301">new capital requirements</ELink> for the largest banks, which would then "face increased pressure to consider breaking themselves up," a stance that has put the former Goldman Sachs Group Inc. investment banker at odds with Wall Street.</Para><Para>Mr. Kashkari left the Treasury in 2009. Later that year, <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703558004574582200194483432"> he joined bond manager</ELink> Pacific Investment Management Co. to help beef up its equity funds. In 2014, <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/neel-kashkari-to-face-jerry-brown-in-california-governors-race-1401872702">he ran for governor of California</ELink> as a Republican, losing to incumbent Gov. Jerry Brown.</Para><Para>Since joining the Minneapolis Fed in 2016, Mr. Kashkari has sounded <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/feds-kashkari-warns-rate-rises-could-drive-economy-into-recession-1513625597">warnings against raising interest rates</ELink>. He voted against all three 2017 rate increases—twice as the lone dissenter—arguing inflation remained short of the Fed's 2% target. He doesn't have a voting role on the rate-setting Federal Open Market Committee this year but said Friday that he backed the rate increase announced this week because it "represented continuity" with what the Fed had said it was going to do. Still, he said he thinks the economy has a ways to go to meet the central bank's job and inflation goals.</Para><Para>Mr. Kashkari said the Fed still operates at a "trust deficit." To counter that, he hosts live-streamed town-hall meetings. He is also active on social media, weighing in on economic issues on Twitter, chronicling his grilling exploits or sharing videos of puppies.</Para><Para>"The Fed had historically been like the Wizard of Oz—no one understood it," he said. "When the financial crisis hit, we needed to do extraordinary things and we needed people to trust us. We need that trust for the future."</Para><Para>Write to Alison Sider at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:alison.sider@wsj.com">alison.sider@wsj.com</ELink></Para><Para>Related</Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fed-super-dove-kashkari-says-he-supports-latest-fed-rate-rise-in-bid-for-continuity-1521821669?tesla=y">Super Dove Kashkari Says He Supports Latest Fed Rate Rise, in Bid For Continuity</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ex-bear-stearns-ceo-off-wall-street-but-still-mixing-it-up-at-the-bridge-table-1521288000">James Cayne: Ex-Bear CEO Now Plays Bridge, Not Markets</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/investor-who-won-big-betting-on-housing-collapse-falters-with-china-bets-1521802810">Kyle Bass: Won Big Betting on Housing Collapse, Now Falters With China Bets</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/last-head-of-bear-stearns-taking-on-wall-street-goliaths-at-guggenheim-1521288000">Alan Schwartz: Last Bear Head Takes on Wall Street</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ten-years-after-the-bear-stearns-bailout-nobody-thinks-it-would-happen-again-1520959233">Nobody Thinks the Bailout Would Happen Again</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-decade-after-bears-collapse-the-seeds-of-instability-are-germinating-again-1521035171">A Decade Later, Seeds of Instability Are Germinating</ELink></Para><Para>* <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://blogs.wsj.com/moneybeat/2018/03/16/how-the-bear-stearns-meltdown-wrecked-something-more-valuable-than-money/">How Bear Wrecked Something More Valuable than Money</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Alison Sider </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fed-official-who-bailed-out-big-banks-is-now-one-of-their-biggest-critics-1521802830" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

